      <para id="id18359982">Mr Brain Cell:</para>
      <list id="id21199339" list-type="bulleted">
        <item>Asks: Man, how hot is it on the sun?<emphasis effect="bold">Answer</emphasis><emphasis effect="bold">: </emphasis></item>
        <item>6 000Â°C (60 x the temperature of boiling water)</item>
      </list>
      <para id="id18207900">Have a group discussion on the following questions:</para>
      <list id="id3461943" list-type="bulleted">
        <item>From which direction does the sun rise in the morning? From the east</item>
        <item>In which direction does the sun set in the evening? In the west</item>
        <item>Where, do you think, does the sun go at night? It goes nowhere; the earth revolves around its own axis; the sun is now shining on a different part of the world.</item>
      </list>
      <para id="id24847219">TIME OF SUNRISE AND SUNSET</para>
      <list id="id20266981" list-type="bulleted">
        <item>Keep record of the sunrise and sunset for two weeks, by having someone bring the newspaper to school every day, so learners can look at the weather forecast. They have to tabulate the sunrise and sunset. They normally get very excited to see how the times change from day to day!</item>
      </list>
